title: Don't Crash on Nullable ViewModels (#784)
message:
Don't Crash on Nullable ViewModels (#784)

* Fix crash bug #780

…at least for the case that I know how to reproduce.

If DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel() returns null,
viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.

The method is declared @Nullable. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s
euphemism for “lie”).

SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without
causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that
null to the view model list.

* Cope with a null ViewModel

ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope
with nulls.

If not for the previous change that makes
DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that
kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the
Recent Notifications screen.

I also put a check in RecentNotificationsListBinder to be safe, but
control doesn’t get there in this case. Perhaps it crashes before then.

Fixes #780

title: Fix Issue 774 and implement stacked notifications (#781)
message:
Fix Issue 774 and implement stacked notifications (#781)

* Step 1 for Issue 774: Unify GCM notifications

Use the notification ID rather than setGroup() to make a
summary notification consistently replace any other
notification.

Next up: Try using Nougat and Wear features to group and
aggregate notifications.

* Implement stacked notifications

* To get stacking, post the individual notifications then a
SummaryNotification.
* Use Notification[Manager]Compat from the latest support lib version to
get their compatibility workarounds. That requires compileSdkVersion 24.
* Still, stacking breaks on KitKat and earlier, so add a workaround.
* Rephrase some notification content text messages to put the useful info
up front so it’s readable when collapsed to one line and even in the
summary view that shows each entry’s title + content in a single line.

Q. Remove the large icon from these notifications to make more room for
the content text?

Q: Should tapping one notification in a stack notifications dismiss all the
others (as it used to do since the summary replaced the previous notifications)? What do people expect? This would esp. matter when there are many accumulated notifications.

* Workaround stack-notification bug on API 21

Use the same workaround as on API 20 KitKat.

* Use the right AndroidStyle.xml file

… to fix the reordered imports.

* update .travis.yml to match build.gradle

to match compileSdkVersion 24, buildToolsVersion '23.0.3'

* Drop large icons from notifications

… to leave more space for informative text.

Set the small icon color to the color named `primary`, which is blue in
release builds, red in debug builds. Set the color in
SummaryNotification, too, so it doesn’t cause all its grouped
notifications to also show their small icons.

* Move the notification overflow count to the summary line

… to make room for 1 more notification on Android M-. Omit
the summary line on N where the app_name or the overflow
count would be redundant, and the count would take extra
work to update when the user swipes away a component
notification.
* Remove another call to the deprecated getColor().
* Show the event code in event-down notification titles, like
other notification types, so the 1-line summary is more
useful, esp. on Android M-.
* I tweaked AndroidStyle.xml to properly wrap method
parameters & arguments, then re-exported it. Android
Studio made the other changes to that file itself.

* fix a unit test broken by the previous change

Fixes #774

title: Fix crash bug #780 (#782)
message:
Fix crash bug #780 (#782)

…at least for the case that I know how to reproduce.

If `DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel()` returns null,
viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.

The method is declared `@Nullable`. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s
euphemism for “lie”).

`SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel()` does return null without
causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that
null to the view model list.

Closes #780

**Summary:** When a user upgrades to the newest version of the app (with an existing Google auth token), we'll recover and register for Firebase in the background

title: Tweak google-services and VCS
message:
Tweak google-services and VCS

Move the default google-services.json (so fresh clones and travis can
build because the gradle plugin requires the file to be present) to the
lowest priority location, and ensure that the flavor-specific locations
are ignored. This way, prod builds can have its file in
android/src/prod/ and a debug build pointing to a dev instance can have
one in android/src/debug/

See this comment:
https://github.com/googlesamples/google-services/issues/54#issuecomment-209646611
for the order of file location searches

 - Massive auth/GCM cleanup. Mainly kills a bunch of static classes which make for spaghetti dependencies and testing difficulties and replaces it all with DI'd controllers

Still TODO (in another pull, though): Update GCM -> Firebase Cloud Messaging APIs

title: Tweak No Data binding logic
message:
Tweak No Data binding logic

If the binder receives invalid data, but there is already data bound,
that means the following case is most likely:
 - There was data available in the local cache that we can display
 - The network call returned an error/still is cached with an empty
   value

This can happen when the user receives a push notification which writes
some data locally, but the remote endpoint has not had its cache
cleaered yet, causing the display to flicker between correct data and no
data view.

Fixes #638

title: Fix live event next/last match bugs
message:
Fix live event next/last match bugs

If the eventbus event doesn't give us anything, hide the container for
the views. This fixes the bug in the case where you firt load next/last
match while there are still matches to go, but then resume the activity
after the last match has been played. This will cause the last match
card to be "stale", still showing the old last match. Now we'll hide it
in that case to produce the proper output.

Additionally, check if ButterKnife is bound during the eventbus
callbacks, since we may be in a resume state where we haven't done so
yet. This will fix crashes trying to access a null view in the onEvent
method, which many execute before `updateData` does or before the
framework initially runs `bindViews`.

Fixes #585

title: Fix buffering for Firebase tickers
message:
Fix buffering for Firebase tickers

If the ticker contains fewer elements than the existing buffer size,
then it'll hang forever waiting for enough items to come through and
fill the buffer.

Buffering is requried since we're pushing items into the Observable at
"for loop" speed, so we need to be able to slow down the processing (see
ResumableRxFirebase).

This now puts a time limit on the buffers, see
http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/rx/Observable.html#buffer%28long,%20java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit,%20int%29

The main downside is the onNext callback is executed every `period` of
time (with empty data). This commit has it at every 5 seconds - also the
max initial loading time. Not sure what the perf implications are.

Can some other people test this out before I merge and see if it affects
perf? It seems like it does to me, but I'm not sure if that's
confirmation bias now that I'm looking for it.

title: Rebind ButterKnife after parent activity stop
message:
Rebind ButterKnife after parent activity stop

It seems like that references to views in the binder were going away
after leaving/coming back to the screen, so it's probably the framework
recreating instances.

BaseAPISubscriber.hasBinderBound is sticky, we we want to reset it when
the parent fragment is stopped so we rebind ButterKnife (and potentially
do other things in the future) if/when we come back.

Fixes #565

to the eventbus :)

title: Refactor LoadTBAData to use Synchronous Retrofit
message:
Refactor LoadTBAData to use Synchronous Retrofit

Instead of hacking around with the reactive versions, do things properly
and add a new declaration that uses the Call<> response. Now we can
ensure that the response was successful and handle the situation
accordingly.

title: Set up framework for no data texts
message:
Set up framework for no data texts

Disclaimer: haven't tested this. But it probably works :P
Steps to implement no data texts:
 1. In each subclass of DatafeedFragment, override getNoDataParams and return an instance of NoDataViewParams containing the drawable and string res ids to show (you can change the params if you want something different)
 2. Make sure each fragment layout has a TextView and an ImageView that can be shown/hidden as needed
 3. In each fragment's onCreateView, call mBinder.setNoDataImageView/setNoDataTextView with the appropriate views
 4. In each subclass of AbstractDataBinder:
  a. In updateData, call setDataBound() if the incoming data is correct and successfully bound. Also call mNoDataBinder.unbindData() to hide no data info
  b. In onComplete, if(!getDataBound()), call mNoDataBinder.bindData(mNoDataParams)
 5. Check TODOs in NoDataBinder (may be other better ways to do it)

title: Fix #406 show the day-of-week with each match time
message:
Fix #406 show the day-of-week with each match time

This distinguishes today's matches from tomorrow's matches and from
yesterday's matches with delayed results (e.g. right now on Carson and
Tesla).

I tried out two approaches. This simple, low-risk approach just prepends
the day-of-week to the formatted time. Would any locales rather append the
day-of-week?

The other approach uses the user's 12/24 hour preference to select the date
format pattern "E HH:mm" or "E hh:mm a" from a string resource, calls
DateFormat.getBestDateTimePattern() on API level >= 18 to allow
locale-specific adjustments and field reorderings, then uses that to format
the Date. Localizing those resources might fight with
getBestDateTimePattern(), so maybe the code should use one of those two.
The app isn't really internationalized yet so the added complexity doesn't
pay off.

A match list might look less busy if entries omitted the day-of-week when
following a list entry with the same day-of-week, but then their day/time
strings wouldn't line up vertically. Also it's not obvious how to pass that
info across adjacent entries, and it's not a time for avoiding risk.

title: Add a JavaDoc comment to EventHelper#shortName()
message:
Add a JavaDoc comment to EventHelper#shortName()

including a link to the corresponding server code.

[After this code review I'll adjust the server code to match and to link
back to the client code. E.g. in the regexp
'...(.*)(District|Regional|Region|...)( Competition| Event| Championship)?'
The '(FIRST Robotics|FRC)?' part matches nothing since (.*) has a "greedy"
quantifier, 'Regional|Region' is the same as 'Region' since there's no
trailing r'\b', and the '( Competition| Event| Championship)?' part has no
effect since nothing looks at the text after the 'District|Regional|...'
part.]

title: Fix #384 Notifications Not Being Marked As Read
message:
Fix #384 Notifications Not Being Marked As Read

See Android Issue 41253: The deleteIntent of the Notification doesn't get
called when the user touches the Notification
https://code.google.com/p/android/issues/detail?id=41253

Workaround: Add a Category to each notification content Intent. When such
an Intent starts an Activity, send the "cancel" Intent that the system
should've sent to dismiss the "read" notification messages.

Contrarywise, don't dismiss notifications when opening the Recent
Notifications activity.

(Possible future: Change the UI so push notifications don't display in a
system notification when Recent Notifications is visible, but still trigger
notification sounds, vibration, and Wear notifications.)

title: Bug fix: rotating the dev settings screen would crash
message:
Bug fix: rotating the dev settings screen would crash

Each Fragment class needs a 0-arg constructor so Android can re-instantiate
it after rotating the screen or a similar event. A non-static inner class
has a hidden outer-this arg, so that doesn't work.

This commit fixes DevSettingsFragment.

The standard recommendation is to have ONLY a 0-arg constructor, but it
seems reasonable to have other constructors that stash the args via
Fragment#setArguments(Bundle) so the 0-arg constructor can retrieve them.

Does UpdateUserModelSettingsTaskFragment() need to do that? This commit at
least makes it safe from NullPointerExceptions.

title: Add info to notification titles
message:
Add info to notification titles

This improves the helpfulness of the lock screen notifications (esp. in
the normal, compact form[1]) and the summary notification (since it lists
push-notification titles).

Score notification title: Add an abbreviated match name, e.g. "Q10".
Upcoming match notification title: Add an abbreviated match name.
Summary notification title: Add the push-notification count.

A bit more concise for small notification areas:
"will be playing" -> "will play",
"which is scheduled" -> "scheduled".

[1] Probably few people know they can expand notifications to see more
lines of text, and expanding isn't great on the lock screen since it opens
the unlock-keypad on top.

title: on FABmyTBA Activity, update model prefs in b.g.
message:
on FABmyTBA Activity, update model prefs in b.g.

As discussed in #342, always close the model settings fragment and
execute the server request in the background. It will Toast after the
request is complete with the status (and color the FAB briefly) to
indicate success or failure.

This couldn't be easily done to the ModelSettingsActivity (which is
launched from the myTBA section for an individual model), because it's a
separate activity that is closed when complete, so there's nothing to
call back to. So we might have to deal with an imperfect UI here for a
bit. Open to better ways to do it...

It'll be doable to make the change, but not in this
timeframe.

title: Fix saving model prefs before load (fixes #317)
message:
Fix saving model prefs before load (fixes #317)

Disables the FAB to save preferences while the settings pane is being
created. When the load is finished, a callback is called to re-enable
the fab. This stops the preferences being saved before they're
populated, causing the default (empty) state to be stored.

fix_event_years Bug fixes

title: Fixed the constant in FIRST_COMP_WEEK that caused a blank 'Week 0' to appear…
message: Fixed the constant in FIRST_COMP_WEEK that caused a blank 'Week 0' to appear when viewing events for 2012. (#78)

title: Shifted a null check to fix a NPE crash when trying to view a blank…
message: Shifted a null check to fix a NPE crash when trying to view a blank activity/intent in the rare case that an event is still loading info even after the loading spinner goes away.

title: Fixed OOB exception when viewing match lists/matches with two teams to an…
message: Fixed OOB exception when viewing match lists/matches with two teams to an alliance (or none in some cases). Only add a third team text/touch listener if there are three teams in an alliance. Otherwise, leave the third slot blank. Doesn't support a 4v0 match for now. However, there isn't any match info from any of the 2001 regionals yet (the only year when 4v0 matches occurred) and I'm not sure if there will be in the near future.

title: Changed match scores to strings so that unknown scores appear as "?" like the TBA site.
message: Changed match scores to strings so that unknown scores appear as "?" like the TBA site.

title: Didn't put a replacement date inside the JsonNull check in…
message: Didn't put a replacement date inside the JsonNull check in SimpleEventDeserializer, so it was throwing an IllegalArgumentException instead. Woops, fixed!

title: Added more JsonNull checks to fix some crashes from spamming event year changes.
message: Added more JsonNull checks to fix some crashes from spamming event year changes.

title: Added size check when getting OPRs, since some events have OPR keys with nothing…
message: Added size check when getting OPRs, since some events have OPR keys with nothing in it. This resulted in a blank "Top OPRs:" being shown. This also resulted in some events not showing "Top OPRs:" despite having stats.

title: Added extra NPE check in PopulateEventInfo to fix a possible crash.
message: Added extra NPE check in PopulateEventInfo to fix a possible crash.

title: Added a placeholder name in the Teams tab in an event for those teams without a…
message: Added a placeholder name in the Teams tab in an event for those teams without a name, similar to what was done in the Teams activity.

title: Added JsonNull checks to fix a crash when loading events with teams without a…
message: Added JsonNull checks to fix a crash when loading events with teams without a team name or location.

title: Switched fragments Changed fragments to be instantiated with a factory method…
message: Switched fragments Changed fragments to be instantiated with a factory method pattern. This leaves the fragments with just empty constructors (which the Android framework expects) and passes all needed values in an arguments Bundle. This allows the framework to properly handle recreating fragments, eliminating some crashing bugs.

title: Fixed minor layout issues that missed my last round of bug checks. Added a nice…
message: Fixed minor layout issues that missed my last round of bug checks. Added a nice animation when switching which year of events is shown.

title: Finished integrating Phil's branch into my own. This encompassed updating…
message: Finished integrating Phil's branch into my own. This encompassed updating layouts, adapters, activities, fragments... pretty much everything. The full extent of what I did is too long for this commit message. I also switched over to using the support library for fragments, activities, and some adapters; this is because the one method we really need, Fragment.getChildFragmentManager(), is only available through the support library or API 17+. This allows us to host fragments within fragments, which we need for the design we want.
